On the other hand what Cicero expresses by opposita is called in astro- nomical language conjunction, σύνοδος, when moon and sun stand near each other iu the heavens, the moon being between the earth and the sun, and in regard to us before the sun, opposita, or sometimes just under it, suppositam which case a total or partial eclipse results. Thales under· stood the causes of the eclipses of the sun and moon so well that he was able to predict one of the sun. See Diog. L. 1, 23 with the remark of Menoge. But this isdoubted by more recent writers on the history of astronomy. See Philol. XXII, p. 550.
